IMHO.<br>
<br>
The only thing you can really plan to camp for is XP, and sometimes that doesn't work out.  You may hope for phat lewt, phat lewt may actually drop - but in the end the only thing you can count on is XP.  Anything above and beyond that is extra.<br>
<br>
NBG allows you to allot that extra to the person who is most immediately improved by it.   Allotting it to someone that will sell it has no immediate effect and will likely not have an effect for some time, as they are busy selling the item and the plat they gain will rest in their bank.<br>
<br>
Poppen hits it on the head, though maybe the word choice is a bit off.  It is about honor, of a sort.  It's about enjoying the fact that you helped another person out, knowing that gear is nice but in the end the pixels mean nothing.  Also, it's about not worrying that some "lootwhore" got the better of me, because it's just pixels.  <br>
<br>
I'm no worse for it, they're still a greedy "whore", I move on... I didn't lose anything, I just saw the bad side of humanity.<br>
<br>
When that fungal tunic drops and the monk gets it from a NBG policy how is anyone else robbed?  The fact it dropped is pure luck - no one laid claim to it before, as probable as the drop is you still can't plan on it.<br>
<br>
It's simple.  You didn't gain anything, but you didn't lose anything either.  <br>
<br>
But, if you play by NBG you get to know the joy of helping a fellow player out - giving that cleric his first bit of donals, that warrior an upgrade to his ykesha, the caster a step up from his O robe.  <br>
<br>
Sometimes you get burned, but that's life, get up, grow up, move on.<br>
<br>
